******
[2]
Date: Sat 27 Aug 2011
Source: Focus Taiwan News Channel, Central News Agency (CNA) report
[edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aLIV&ID=201108270030


Hospital admits mistake in organ transplant procedures
------------------------------------------------------
The National Taiwan University Hospital (NTUH) said on Saturday [27
Aug 2011] that its transplant team did not follow standard operating
procedures and check test results on the computer before transplanting
organs from an HIV-infected donor into 4 patients earlier this week.
NTUH spokesman Tan Ching-ting said at a news conference that its
physicians only checked on results of HIV tests on the organs with the
hospital's lab people by phone, leading to a misunderstanding.

Transplant team members heard a member of the lab say the test results
were "non-reactive" when in fact they were "reactive" and proceeded to
perform 4 transplant procedures, Tang said. A 5th organ was sent to
National Cheng Kung University Hospital in Tainan, which apparently
suffered a similar oversight. Speaking on the same occasion, Hung
Chien-ching, an attending physician in NTHU's infectious disease
department, said the hospital did not know the donor was an HIV
carrier. Local health departments usually do not expose carriers'
identities over privacy protection concerns. "Before our team
performed the transplants, it had no way to know the donor was an HIV
carrier," he said.

Earlier on Saturday [27 Aug 2011], Yao Ke-wu, director of the Bureau
of Health of Hsinchu City, said the donor was a legally listed HIV
carrier in Taipei, who received treatment there until July [2011]
before being referred to Hsinchu City for continued care. The
incident, Yao said, exposed a major loophole in the domestic organ
transplant system.

The Department of Health (DOH) said earlier in the day that NTUH, one
of Taiwan's most prestigious health care institutions, transplanted
the organs of an HIV infected donor on Wednesday [24 Aug 2011] without
realizing it, putting 5 organ transplant recipients at high risk of
contracting AIDS. It marked the 1st time in Taiwan that organ
transplants might lead to recipients falling victim to AIDS, the DOH
said.

The hospital informed the DOH of the incident on Saturday [27 Aug
2011], said Shih Wen-yi, deputy director-general of the DOH's Centers
for Disease Control. According to Shih, the hospital has offered
emergency anti-AIDS medications to the 5 organ transplant recipients.
Yao Ke-wu, director of the Bureau of Health of Hsinchu City, said the
donor was a legally listed HIV carrier in Taipei, who sustained a
serious head injury after accidentally falling from a high-rise
building on Wed 24 Aug 2011. As his condition was not promising, the
37 year old's family took the initiative to contact NTUH to arrange
the transfer of his organs, Yao said. An NTUH transplant team rushed
to the city's Nanmen Hospital to remove the man's organs and brought
them to Taipei for transplant into 5 different patients, Yao said. The
DOH has demanded that NTUH present a complete report on the incident
in 3 days.

Shih said the hospital has apologized to the patients and their
families as well as briefed them on the situation. To the best of his
knowledge, Shih said the hospital has consistently conducted HIV
testing on organ donors. "We don't know at the moment what went wrong
in this case, which has left 5 innocent organ recipients facing AIDS
risks," Shih said.

HIV is a lentivirus that causes acquired immunodeficiency syndrome, a
condition in humans in which progressive failure of the immune system
allows life-threatening opportunistic infections and cancers to
thrive.

[byline: Chen Ching-fang, Sofia Wu]

